,Recommended,270850,8896455,"Posted: 28 January, 2014",all,Mr. McSinister,"Calling it a simulator is a bit of a  stretch. When I hear the word simulator in a gaming context, I think of intracacy and attention to detail in design, and an attempt by the developer to make the experience as close as possible to the real thing (whatever it may be). That said, Car Simulator 2014 is definitely not a simulator. As others have said, it's more like a car mechanic themed puzzle game.The gameplay is relatively simple: you get three different functions when interacting with the parts of several different cars (analyze, remove, and install). Parts on the vehicle are colour coded, ranging from red (bad) to green (good), with percentage values. You'll get repair orders, always with some description that will hint at the problem (e.g. ""my car won't start""), and then you use the tools and the aforesaid functions to solve it. You start out with a basic garage, but eventually you progress to two better shops; the second shop comes with the ability to path test vehicles (a minigame that analyzes suspension and brakes) and, additionally, a module for chip tuning vehicles in the last. In all of the shops you have the ability to take drivable vehicles on a test drive, which is yet another way to check for damage to parts without having to tear the vehicle apart - it's not very fun, and a little clumsy, but it gets the job done.What I like:* There are several different models of vehicles, many with different arrangements of parts (e.g. ""V6"" versus four cylinder, 4x4 versus 2wd)* The visuals are nice for a game of such small scale* Some progression (spend money to make bolt removal quicker, for example)* The interface is simple and relatively intuitive: you can hide the car body and turn on a filter to show the condition of partsWhat I didn't like:* Realism isn't a big factor in the design of this game at all (e.g. an air filter will keep the engine from running)* The number of parts is quite limited; some front-end pieces, brakes and wheels, and stuff around the motor - you'll never see the inside of the crankcase* Customers don't pay for parts or labour; they pay a flat rate, and your profit is what's left over after you've bought the replacement parts (or repaired the limited number of repairable ones)* Despite the limited progression above, the game becomes very repetitiveSummary:If you're looking for a simple (if not simplistic) puzzle-like mechanic game, then you might get some enjoyment out of it. But, if you're looking for a proper simulation of car repair or running a shop, then you may be disappointed with the limits of Car Mechanic Simulator 2014. I was hoping for the latter, and I was disappointed by the limitations of the game, but I did enjoy tooling around with it for a few hours."
,Recommended,270850,8901066,"Posted: 29 January, 2014",all,gicek,"Fun puzzle game. Executed reasonably well. If you ever played Gearhead Garage, then you're in for a treat. It is essentialy that game, but in a modern package. It is in some cases much more realistic than Gearhead Garage. There are more aspects of being a mechanic than just assembling and disassembling cars depicted. I really liked the game, but i have few things that are less than ideal.Unfortunately you cannot disassemble the whole car- engine is almost monolitic, there are parts of the suspension that are non interactive. Also there is no way to disassemble the body of the car.Part of the game is test-driving a car. Unfortunately it is almost the same every time. Car drives the same way no matter what faults it has- you don't hear additional noises parts of the suspension are shot, there is no indication that steering is off or if there are problems with the ignition or anything else. The only diferences between cars are acceleration rates and interior design. It works like this- there are parts of the suspension that cannot be examined to see if they are broken unless you disassemble them or take the test drive. Also sometimes it is required by a client for you to test drive the car and there is no way around it. All these things make the test drive fun for one maybe two times, then it becomes more of a chore than fun. Thankfully test driving a car takes about 1-2 minutes, so unless you play for a long time it will not bother you much. Don't get me wrong- i absolutely like the idea of test driving a car. I just would expect it to be more consequential and let the player to figure out what's wrong with the car instead of giving him an answer.The last thing i'm going to complain about is number car models and parts you can buy. I hope developers will add more cars and parts to the game, but now there are two different engines and i belive there are 3 types of suspension, but there are no real diferences in them beside names of the parts that were used.To sum up- I played 6 hours and I think i saw all the content there is to see, but i cannot say for certain. What i saw so far was mostly good. If you like this type of game (which is essentialy a 3d puzzle game) you'll have a good time, but keep in mind before you decide if you are going to buy it- at the time of writing this, game is somewhat limited, there is no much variety when it comes to cars. Game is rather easy, but i believe there is almost no competition- if you look for similar things look for gearhead garage (a bit dated, but i think still playable)."
