,Not Recommended,270850,8860848,"Posted: 26 January, 2014",all,0x80,"Overall, the game felt more like a beta, or an early development concept than a fully fledged simulator. Decent in some respects, but not phenomenal. Most of the top-most ""helpful"" reviews have listed all the obvious deficiencies of the game. There are a few I'd like to add, along with some suggestions for what would make the game better:1.) Improve the camera behavior; feels like you have to fight the camera to focus the tiny dot reticle on an interface target. If I've tried every mouse sensitivity, and still have to adjust the mouse an average of 5 times every time I try to interact with something, there's a problem with the interface design.2.) If you must include a test track feature without much ability to control look camera or any rear-view features, add some flashing directional arrows or something to tell the driver where to go.3.) Also, if the test track is something that I just drive a car through demolition derby style, from highlight pad to highlight pad, requiring no thought from the player in actualy formulating the diagnosis, maybe it's a feature that should just be done away with entirely, or reduced to something in the game menu along the lines of ""send for test drive"". Since it requires me to do nothing except pilot a car in the same repetitive fashion around the same track, it just feels like a time waster or a pointless minigame. Since I'm not actually doing repairs with this feature, just basic piloting of a simplistic drive simulation, it detracts from the point of the game -- to actually repair cars.4.) If possible, add some real life makes/models to the game. This was probably the one thing I found myself most yearning for while playing, and would truly make the game engaging. To actually be able to work on, say, my own car, or some recently released model of car, or some exotics, classics, etc. would be truly amazing. If licensing or IP constraints make this feature impossible, I'm sure there are some foreign or outdated models of cars that can be reasonably cloned. Like older cars no longer in production, or made by defunct manufacturers who wouldn't sue you for copying their schematics. The point here is not simulating the actual mechanical issues of any particular model, but rather, letting players actually dismantle particular models that are interesting.5.) If trying to simulate real mechanical challenges seems too daunting, consider adding a feature for players to design their own repair missions to share with other players. Players with a lot of experience with a particular model might come up with something really clever to challenge fellow players with. Such a feture would help build a following for the game.Conclusion: overall, the game philosophy seems to be shaky: why check obd if all it consists of is clicking ""check obd"", then watching a little bitmap image of a low res display pop up and tell me I'm checking OBD. Can we actually simulate an OBD unit somehow, like, make me look for a data port? If I'm going to take a car to a test track, can we figure out how to actually make the player responsible for diagnosing a problem? If I'm going to repair a part, is there any way that I can actually learn to repair a part, or be responsible for fumbling with a facsimily of what it takes to repair each part? Again, if it's not requiring the player to actually be a mechanic to some degree, it just feels like a time waster. What aspect of mechanic behavior is it simulating?Overall, good start on a cool idea. Not many mechanic simulators exist. I would love to see this idea develop further, because as a simulator it seems to fall short."
