,Recommended,270850,10904186,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,Sekiyu,"All the fun of being a shade tree mechanic without any of the mess, busted knuckles or that awesome feeling of dread that you've broken your car beyond repair. You're presented with various customers' auto problems that range from the very specific ""I hit a giant pothole and destroyed my left side suspension"" to the very vague ""my car makes a rattling sound on startup."" You can visually inspect various areas of the car, or go on a test drive, or use an OBD scanner and later in the game you get access to a suspension and brake tester. You have the choice of buying new parts or buying used parts of dubious quality from the junkyard to make the repairs with. My favorite part of this game is that it lets you keep all the messed up parts in your inventory. Pretty soon you'll have a nice collection of busted water pumps, torn up clutch wheels and a mountain of worn out shocks and springs. The game gives you an option to sell these (presumably to the same junkyard you buy stuff from), or you can be a completely unethical thief and slap the busted parts on a later customer's car, taking their good parts for another customer. See, the game has certain milestones you have to do in order to pass a scenario, like ""replace oil and air filter."" It doesn't care if the rest of the components of the car go down in quality, as long as the parts the scenario cares about get fixed. So sure, I replaced Mr. Smith's dead battery, just like the game wanted me to, but unbeknownst to him, I also swapped out his perfectly good gearbox and ignition system with almost broken ones from Mr. Johnson who was my previous customer. In the scenario where I had to fix the guy's left side suspension, I simply flipped the parts from his good right side onto his left side, then sent him on his way. If this game has taught me anything, it's not about learning how to fix cars, rather it is to WATCH YOUR MECHANIC LIKE A HAWK in real life. I think I spend more time essentially screwing over each one of my customers than I do actually repairing their vehicles. Remember that junkyard? I regularly buy crap from them and swap it into my customers' cars, just so I can have a good copy of a part when I need it, without having to pay full price for a good one."
