,Recommended,270850,13144465,"Posted: 29 November, 2014",all,DeevFactor,"This is a relatively decent auto repair simulation game, and one of the billion simulator titles on the grand Steam store,  You are of course an mechanic, whose job is to look at noteboards and take on tasks from the various faceless and bodyless customers who toss money as you at a drop of a hat.  How can you tell what parts might be damaged, you ask?  Luckily, you have the ability to see the color-coded conditions of the parts that need relplacing (sic).  With your amazing powers, you can use your mouse to remove and install parts by the art of clicking. Click the empty space. Click the bolts. Hold the mouse button!You also get to drive the cars on the lifeless test track.  If you feel like breaking the stone cold laws of the test track, go nuts!  Crash that car all you want!  No damage model ahoy!  Never worry about wrecking the car that you're supposed to fix ever again!While you take your time relplacing (sic) those damaged parts, you can listen to a soundtrack of club and dance music that you may not really care to search for on Youtube, unless you're absolutely desperate to be the first to comment ""I heard this song in Car Mechanic Simulator! :D""  Aside from the goofy nitpicks, the game does a good job at making the car repair process simple, making it like a puzzle game of sorts as you figure out what they're connected to."
