,Recommended,270850,9567927,"Posted: 19 March, 2014",all,Whitey,"I'm yes and no on my recommendation for this game. This is the groundwork for a game I'd love. Kind of a long reading following but this'll give anyone looking into game an exact idea of what they're jumping in to. This game is a nice buy for car/mechanical enthusiasts. This game would be best set up for someone who is just getting into cars, but isn't very familiar with their mechanicals. You could learn how basic parts go together and what some of their effects may be. However, to advance through this game at a decent pace you need a little prior mechanical knowledge. For example, you may be told that you need to find a power issue and not know that the fuel pump or fuel filter could be the problem.The problem with this game though, is that no matter whether you're a mechanic yourself or someone learning, The game will have become mind-numbingly monotonous about 3/4 of the way through. At this point you'll have seen all the vehicles, driven them, taken care of every problem, and you'll be running on repeated problems so you can buy all the Learning Book upgrades. All the concepts are presented less than halfway through the game, then the later garages simply allow you to diagnose parts faster. At the time of writing this I quit the campaign about 6/7 of the way through out of sheer boredom.If you've ever played the 1989 Street Rod DOS/Commodore 64 game, then you've played this game. Infact, in the first garage, the game can be seen lying on one of the shelves as a neat little reference. I would recommend searching around for Street Rod, since it's a nice little game to play. The only problem is that this game only has slightly more detail than Street Rod did 25 years ago.In Street Rod, you changed wheels and clicked the bolts much like you do here. You changed out engines, removed heads, carburetors, and upgraded your car in general. After upgrading, you'd go do a basic NES-era street race to earn other cars or money and continue until you beat the fastest racer in town.In Car Mechanic Simulator, I'd say you have a little more variety of detail but not where most would enjoy. Put graphical detail of 3D models aside. When it comes down to it, you're changing air intakes, timing chain/belts, suspension parts, gearbox parts rarely, and the exhaust. You will never touch the engine block, the sub-frames, or any body work (on that note, the feature list specifically states that you will do body work). These parts are off-limits and can't be removed. You will never be able to customize any setup; it's Part-On, Part-Off, and what condition the part is in.The car models themselves are nicely detailed, but are static and feel a bit bland with the way they are rendered. The cars are modeled after real-life cars, but use slightly different design and names. Most of them will be European/Japanese economy cars or small vans/SUVs. The 2010+ Mustang replica is the most distinguished car, but oddly one of the SUVs seem to the fastest car you can test drive.As parts wear, they begin to show slight signs of rust, which is a nice detail. That said, parts are fixed. There's two engine designs: I4 and V6. The two engines are the same in each iteration, and the V6 will sometimes have a RWD dif or 4WD dif with an additional driveshaft. Also, both engines are always transversely mounted, which is a bit odd considering most V6s in this game are RWD rather than FWD.Gameplay wise, there are a few minor annoyances. While part selection in general is nice, there are times when you'll find yourself clicking to a part 5+ times because of the cursor trying to select a part that's behind the one you want to click. Certain parts, while obviously accessible from your current position (under the car, left side wheel well, etc), can't be touched unless you exit the current area, walk around, access the ""proper"" area, and then remove the part. Often, the camera will zoom or align to an impossible angle to remove the bolts you just selected, so you'll have to fiddle around and zoom out to remove the part. Occasionally, the bolt removal will glitch and you'll have to move the camera to be able to click the bolt again. You'll find yourself constantly moving between nearby areas and lifting the car up and down repeatedly to reach nearby parts. One of the bigger annoyances was the removal of air filters and exhaust parts.  To remove the air filter, you have to remove the plastic engine cover, the tube, the MAF sensor, the cover, and finally the filter (VS just taking the cover off in real life). God forbid you have to remove the exhaust manifold or the catalytic converter. You will have to start at the back of the car, removing every section of exhaust until you reach the desired part. In real life, you'd either drop the whole assembly or simply remove the problem section by itself. These little things, while not that big a deal by themselves, can become annoying after a short amount of time.Also, never buy used parts. Just don't. Often the game requires the replaced parts be of a very high condition and often the random part will be in the green and still not be accepted as a replacement. In regards to replacement parts, often you are not told what the complete requirement of repair is. While not knowing a problem is true to real mechanic shops, some work orders (goals to complete a repair) simply don't give you the full goals. One example in an early mission is how you're given a work order to ""Do an basic examination of my engine."" Do a full examination, and the requirement isn't fulfilled. Turns out you have to just replace broken parts even if the service is not requested. This causes confusion, as early on in the game, you're given specifics that ask for examination but not service. Perhaps the work orders need to be re-written.Finally, a small personal gripe of my own. The game feels like a hospital bedroom. Everything feels stark and bland. Everything on the cars are perfect save for part discoloration. There's no character to any of the vehicles or the locales (save for the first garage itself). Perhaps if there was unique body damage, difference between cars (other than color), or visual dirt/grime and broken part models it would feel a bit more lively.Over all though, this is a fun game for the auto enthusiast for a few hours. I'd recommend it to anyone who likes cars and wants to learn the basic setup of car mechanicals. I feel at the current time it's more of a $10 game rather than $20. I'll have to see how the game evolves with updates, but as the core game is now I'm going to let the last of the campaign sit. I want so badly to have a modern, high-definition version of Street Rod or Gearhead Garage. This is a step in the right direction. I'd pick this game up to support the developers and to help show that there's a market for this kind of game."
,Recommended,270850,9928453,"Posted: 25 April, 2014",all,Dsr1shot,"Awesome starter game if your looking to get into the automotive industry, personally it helped me alot :)Recomend this game 100%"
,Recommended,270850,9784125,"Posted: 10 April, 2014",all,Challenger,"Car Mechanic Simulator is a fun game where you can make quick progress. Perhaps the game might be even more enjoyable with a wheel and pedal setup, but I think it is very playable with just keyboard and mouse. I would like to see the business end of the game developed a bit further, and a wider variety of vehicles available for the clients. I understand there is a 4x4 add-on in development, but I think body work, and paint might be content the users would like to see in future versions."
,Recommended,270850,22985947,"Posted: 14 May, 2016",all,Snowmind,"Car Mechanic Simulator Complete Edition is a quite roundup representation of a modern garage shop, its tools and procedures (later on). The majority of the jobs (tasks) require you to solve some mechanical or other problem to complete the job, which becomes harder and more complex as you advance. But the whole car experience is presented well enough, even for people without the know how of the inner workings of a car, e.g. its engine, electrics, suspension etc to be able to grasp and visualise each aspect quite clearly from earlier on. No need for a manual either, as the examine tool is enough to help you identify the majority of the problems in earlier jobs. The knowledge can then be used later on in the game to solve more complex (or vague) faults having learned by now where to look (if only it was that easy in real life!).The release of Car Mechanic 2015 has improved almost every aspect of the 2014 one but hasn't reduced it's worth. Mostly the improvements are over small niggles which we were used to anyways, such as lack of achievements, multiple jobs, the annoying auto zoom in/out of the examined part, inventory sort, lack of keybinds, cursor slip in window mode, etc etc Also the 2 addons included in the ""Complete Edition"", the ""4x4"" and the ""1/4 mile"" add little value overall and should have been included in the main game, as they are just distractions overall.I would recommend Car Mechanic Simulator Complete Edition to anyone that likes puzzle games as almost all the jobs given require you to investigate an existing car fault(s) and fix them as cheap as possible. Also would recommend to anyone that wants to learn about the anatomy of a car as a learning tool, as it does demonstrate quite accurately some of the main aspects of a car, which otherwise would need to spend a long time in a garage to visualise.And with the 75%-80% off sale this week from steam, makes this a worthy addition to everyones' library."
