76561198053220595,Recommended,270850,13628084,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,Nomad_One,"I purchased Car Mechanic Simulator 2014 for less than $4. I’ve played a good 17 plus hours so far. For less than $4, I got my money’s worth. At full price however, I don’t think it’s really worth it.For one, it is very unrealistic. You can’t rebuild an engine in this game or even replace one.They have a used car part option to save money, but it is completely useless. Often times, I buy a part from here only to either sell it back because it is damaged/broken or the game wants you to buy a brand new one instead; but you don’t find that out until you reassemble the car back together only to see that the checkmark box on the paper is still unchecked. Only a very few times it was necessary but that was far in between and you waste a lot of time (trial and error) in doing so.There is a progressive system but it’s pretty basic. There are only four things to level up: your tools (to unbolt things quicker), business management (to increase money after each fix), better mechanic (at the start, a few parts will already be checked for you), and price discount on parts (new parts costs less with each level up). Each category can be leveled up ten times and then it maxes out.There is a bank loan option but I have never used it. I never needed to borrow money during my time of play. All I did was found the part that needed repair; repaired it or bought a new one and replaced it and pretty much did the minimal until the checkmark box was checked. I didn’t go the extra mile and replaced parts that were in yellow or in orange because that would be wasting time/money.Overall, the game is repetitive and does get boring after a while. The game starts you off with some easy fixes then it gradually progresses into harder or multiple fixes. Sometimes, the problem is given to you very broadly like “the engine won’t start, find the problem.” Other times it is given to straight forward, “change my oil.” You get three things that help you test most of the parts like the suspension, brakes, starter, alternator, etc. There are four colors that each part will display to determine its wear: green, yellow, orange, and red. Green means the part is new or in excellent condition. Yellow means it is okay. Orange means it is about to go out (does not mean you need to replace it though). Red means it’s worn out or broken and needs to be replaced. All you have to do, to be successful in this game, is replace the red parts and ignore the rest. Viola! I’ve had four garage upgrades (they upgrade by themselves after doing a number of fixes for each garage). I’ve maxed out all my upgrades (level 10 in each category). If I had to give this game a grade it would be a B-. It’s okay, but it could be a lot better."
