,Recommended,270850,9920616,"Posted: 24 April, 2014",all,therealstubot,"As a car enthusiast, I found the game to be overly simplified. The interface exaggerates the monotonous aspects of working on cars, while skipping entirely the actual difficulties and triumphs. The main workflow consists of getting a car with a job sheet. The sheet has a vague problem and a dollar amount you'll be paid if you fix the problem. The first assumption made here is that the person who wrote the job sheet knew what the problem was but failed to tell you. They also figured out how much it would cost for you to fix the problem and are charging the car owner that amount. If you fix exactly the problem, you will be profitable. This is a very flawed model since it gives no penalty for diagnosis. You can tear the entire car apart, find the item that has the most amount of wear, if that item can be replaced or repaired for the amount on the job sheet, then it's likely your problem. Rarely, the problem can be 2 or more parts that are marginal.There are several ""makes"" of car in this game, and several different configurations. Most cars and minivans are 4 cylinder, front wheel drive, suv's are all wheel drive, and a few performance cars are v6 (LOL) with rear wheel drive. All cars share most of the same parts. A front strut for the suv fits the economy car, performance car, minivan, everything. There is no confusion about parts at all. The air filter fits everything, as does exhaust pipes, mufflers, cats, brake calipers, brake shoes, end links, shocks, struts, fuel pump, fuel filter, spark plugs, ignition modules, and about a dozen other parts.The mechanics of the game are tedious. You get your car and job sheet. You have to figure out which part to replace, but some of the parts you cannot diagnose till you've taken other parts off. For example, if you want to diagnose any suspension component, you have to remove the wheel before you can diagnose anything else. Once the wheel is removed, you can diagnose a layer of components. Diagnosis consists of either selecting diagnose mode, and clicking on the part, or removing the part. Diagnosing the part makes it turn a color from green to red, with green being the 100% effective and red being 1% effective. It appears that anything below 30% is your bad part, with 17% being the most common threshold for failed part. Remove the part, go to the computer and buy another part, sell the bad part on the used part market, and then install the new part. Put everything back together again. Get paid, rinse, repeat till you're sick of it, which for me was about 2 weeks. One area in particular that bugs me is the brake caliper removal sequence. I have removed brake calipers many times, from many different cars, trucks and motorcycles. in every case, the brake pads stayed in the caliper when I removed the caliper. The game has the brake pads stuck to the rotors, so an additional step is needed to remove the pads.The problems encountered are textbook, and the solutions are also textbook. Anyone who knows about fixing cars will know immediately what the problem is when reading the job sheet. Could this 'game' be used to gain experience in fixing cars... maybe. One would understand more fully what each component was and how it fits into the whole, and how it's failure would impact the whole. The part about the actual work, I believe would only help someone by giving them a general idea of where on a car that item lives. The work portion is so over simplified as to be a great source of laughs for the first 100 times, then tedious boredom after that. There is no searching for the correct sized socket, then discovering you need the deep wall, and don't have one in that size, or picking the wrong size, and rounding off the bolt, so now you have to use a pipe wrench and buy a new bolt... or discovering you cannot fit your hand into the space provided so you make an elaborate contraption of extensions and universal joints only to discover you didn't need to take that bolt out after all. There's nothing about anti-seize, lock-tite, assembly lube, torque wrenches, impact wrenches, nothing at all about tools. I never had to dig out the welder, sawzall, hammer, prybar, gloves or safety glasses during the game, which makes it totally unrealistic. None of the bolts are ever stuck, rusted, or broken. They're always easy to remove, and install. I never burned my hand on a hot exhaust, or got shocked by a faulty spark plug wire, or got battery acid on my good jeans, or spilled oil all over the engine and had a smoke bomb when the car was started. Also, you cannot install parts out of sequence, so the all too common scenario of discovering you forgot to install the wheel bearing seal after you finished putting everything back together never happens.I cannot really imagine an audience for this game. Maybe servicemen overseas who miss working on their cars, or prison inmates... A teenager should have their own jalopy to work on and learn from. An adult inclined toward this will have a project car to work on, and certainly will be working on it instead of pretending to work on it with this game. Someone who is considering this line of work as a vocation won't get an accurate picture with this sim, but will get a very general idea of the workflow. Guys like me see this as a novelty and buy it to be disappointed. Perhaps someone with less hands on experience would benefit, or enjoy the simulation. The design and artwork for the sim is good. I will recommend this sim/game for people curious about working on cars. If you already know how to work on cars, pass on this."
