,Recommended,270850,11174106,"Posted: 10 July, 2014",all,INCONCEIVABLE!,"For a game that calls itself a ""simulator,"" there are several aspects of this game that fall far too short of the real-life experience of working on cars.The first mistake I noticed is the missing human element. In this game, you will find no blank stares or slow mumbles. There are no memorable answers to simple questions, such as people claiming to own a Honda Elantra. The customers usually know what's wrong with their cars and leave understandable notes on the work order, which allows you to quickly find and correct the current problem. I cannot begin to explain how far from reality this actually is.The another jab to the title of ""simulator"" comes from the ease of installation or removal of parts. As any grease monkey will testify, parts just don't come off that easily. I was also sad to find that there was no way to curse at the vehicle for being difficult. The mechanic you play as must be a ghost, as you'll find that starters, located next to the transmission, are installed and removed through the engine bay.Lastly, the cars are all clean. There is no grime to wash off, there are no fingernails lined with black grease. You will not find bandages on your arms and fingers because there are no impact or puncture wounds to heal. No mud, no oil, no antifreeze, no blood. It's all so easy.God I wish it was like this in reality."
